===Etymology===
1820, from {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|gourmet|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|gourmet|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|groumet|lang=fro||wine broker, valet in charge of wines, servant}} from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|grommes|lang=fro||manservant}}, of {{etyl|gem|en}} origin, akin to {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|grom|grom, grome|lang=enm|boy, valet, servant}}, of unknown origin, perhaps from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|*grōma||male child, boy, youth}} from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|grōwan||to grow}}. More at {{term|groom|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ɡoʊɹˈmeɪ/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪ}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# {{context|of food|lang=en}} [[fine]]
#: '''''Gourmet''' coffee is just like regular coffee, only better.''
#: ''We need to go to the '''gourmet''' grocery store to get the exotic ingredients for this recipe.''

====Usage notes====
'''Gourmet''' has become somewhat [[debased]] by marketing usage, and is considered by some a [[pretentious]] [[middlebrow]] term. Such users tend to prefer terms such as {{term|artisanal}} (emphasizing the craft) for fine food.

